Apps Script still uses the JavaScript `new Date()` definition for dates, though when you  use `date.setSeconds(1000)` the date gets converted to Unix time. Google uses Unix time in milliseconds.

Calling `date.setSeconds()` **changes the variable date even when calling it inside** `newDate = date.setSeconds(1000)`.

You can fix this by with:
```lang-js
function myFunction() {
  var date = new Date()
  var newDate = new Date(unixTimeConverter(date).setSeconds(1000));
}

function unixTimeConverter(n) {
  return new Date(n);
}
```

